images.location: Foundation - Retaining wall and footing detail
images.summary: This detail illustrates a foundation system for a retaining wall. The retaining wall itself is 8 inches thick and constructed of 25 MPa concrete. It is reinforced with 15M rebar, including two 15M bars at the top perimeter of the wall, and continuous 15M horizontal and vertical bars spaced at 16 inches on center. The footing supporting the retaining wall is 3'-6" wide and 12" thick, identified as R/W. The footing contains (6) 15M continuous rebar and 15M bent dowels that are 36" long vertically. Additionally, 15M horizontal bars are spaced at 16" on center, with 3" bottom cover to the rebar. The detail shows the footing bearing on undisturbed soil. A 6" concrete slab is shown adjacent to the foundation. The overall height from the top of the footing to the top of the retaining wall is indicated as 3'-10". A steel lid is referenced as per D3. The detail is labeled FW2 and is noted as Not To Scale (N.T.S.).

images.summary: This detail illustrates a foundation wall (FW1) and its supporting footing. The concrete wall is 8 inches thick with a compressive strength of 25 MPa. It sits on a 6-inch concrete slab. The foundation footing is 8 inches wide and 24 inches deep, with a compressive strength of 20 MPa. Reinforcement includes two 15M continuous bars within the footing and two 15M continuous bars at the top of the foundation wall, similar to other door openings. Vertical reinforcement in the footing consists of 15M bars spaced at 36 inches on center, with 48 inches of cover. Horizontal reinforcement in the footing is 1-15M bar at grade. Dowels of 15M x 24" are also provided at 36 inches on center. The detail shows anchor bolts of 1/2" diameter spaced at 48 inches on center, securing a sill plate on a 1/4" sill gasket to the top of the foundation wall. The overall height from the top of the footing to the top of the foundation is indicated as 6'-6", and the height of the concrete wall above the slab is 3'-2". The footing has a 3-inch cover below and the wall has a 4-inch cover below.

A note indicates that HSS 60mm x 6mm beams are spaced at 11" o.c. unless otherwise noted on the plan. The detail also includes notes regarding venting, lighting, and access to a pit below the steel platform as per code, and specifies that all steel is welded to each other unless otherwise noted (U.N.O.). The dimensions shown are 1'-0", 3'-0", and 3'-0" for various sections of the foundation and platform structure.

images.location: Slatted floor detail for tractor support
images.summary: This detail illustrates a "DI SLAT FLOOR DETAIL" designed to support a tractor. The primary structural elements are HSS (Hollow Structural Section) beams. The notes specify that tractor tires must be supported by 3-HSS 60mm x 6mm beams spaced at 5 inches on center. All other HSS 60mm x 6mm beams are to be spaced at a maximum of 11 inches on center. These HSS beams are required to be a minimum of 16 feet long, potentially spanning continuously over HSS 3"x3"x1/4" beams. The detail also indicates a maximum storage load capacity of 100 PSF for straw bales and specifies a minimum of 300W steel for construction. Steel anchors are to be hot-dip galvanized (HDG). The dimensions provided for the "5460 MASSEY FERGUSON" tractor include a wheelbase of 100.5", length of 169.3", width of 79.3", cab height of 109.1", and tire width of 16", with a maximum weight of 4524 kg. The visual representation shows a plan view of the tractor positioned on the slatted floor system, with the HSS beams forming the slatted surface. The scale of the detail is indicated as 1/4" = 1'-0".

images.location: Wall assembly – typical stud wall bracing detail
images.summary: This detail illustrates the "B2 STUD WALL DOUBLE BRACE DETAIL" for a typical stud wall assembly. It shows two primary connection types: a "TOP CONNECTION" and a "BOTTOM CONNECTION" for diagonal bracing. The bracing members are identified as "2x6 DIAGONAL BRACE". The notes specify that the 2x6 brace is to be continuous and end at the stud connection to the plate, and should not be notched into studs. Braces are to be installed at approximately 45-degree angles. The "TOP CONNECTION" shows "DOUBLE SOLID BLOCKING BETWEEN STUDS" fastened with (6) 3\" nails through the face and (3) nails through the stud into each end of each block. Additionally, (12) 3\" common spiral nails are used for each brace at the top and bottom of the wall. The "BOTTOM CONNECTION" details "3-PLY SOLID BLOCKING BETWEEN STUDS TYP." fastened similarly with (6) 3\" nails through the face and (3) nails through the stud into each end of each block. It also specifies (2) 3\" common spiral nails for each stud, typically. For the bottom connection of the brace itself, (3) 3\" common spiral nails are used through a 2x5 plate (or 2x8 plate) into each stud end grain. The detail also indicates the use of (2) 3/8\" wedge anchors, typically at each brace location, to secure the wall to the foundation or slab. The notation "N.T.S." indicates the drawing is not to scale.

The visual representation shows a steel plate with multiple bolt holes, indicating a bolted connection. Dimensions provided clarify the geometry of the connection. images.summary: This detail illustrates the bracing system for roof trusses, primarily using 2x4 lumber. It specifies the installation of diagonal bracing, including 'X' bracing on opposite sides of trusses at endwalls, as indicated by the annotation '2x4 DIAGONAL "X" BRACE ON OPPOSITE SIDE OF TRUSS AT ENDWALLS WHERE SPECIFIED ELSEWHERE'. The detail also shows how to anchor these diagonal braces to laterals using four 3\" nails at the intersection of truss web and truss lateral. Struts are specified as 2x4 lumber, 5'-0\" long, attached to top and bottom truss web members with two 3\" nails each. A critical instruction is to lap diagonal bracing (minimum of 2 trusses) to ensure it extends fully from the top chord to the bottom chord, as noted by 'LAP 2x4 DIAGONAL (MIN. 2 TRUSSES) TO ENSURE DIAGONAL BRACE EXTENDS COMPLETELY FROM TOP CHORD TO BOTTOM CHORD OF TRUSS'. The spacing of the 2x4 diagonal bracing is to be determined by the bracing designer, with a maximum spacing of 48'-0\" mentioned. Butt joints for 2x4 laterals are to be tight and centered on the truss web at all splice locations. The detail clearly labels the 'TRUSS TOP CHORD', 'TRUSS WEB MEMBER', and 'TRUSS BOTTOM CHORD', showing how the bracing connects to these primary truss components.
